defaultn this issue.
defaultJudicial reviewdefault10.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe “next steps” document at 2.18 – 2.20 states that there will be some limited change to the proposals for legal aid for permission work for judicial review. It forecasts a separate consultation, which is the subject of the 
defaultJudicial Review: Further proposals for reform 
default(Cm 8703) consultation. Chapter seven, in particular, addresses these matters. 
default11.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTime constraints prevent us from, at this point, offering 
defaulta
default detailed analysis though we make the following observations.
default12.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFirst, the essence of the 
defaultoriginal rationale and the 
defaultoriginal proposals remains. 
default As the 
defaultJudicial Review: Further Proposals
default paper notes at paragraph 20, the proposals “are intended to act as a disincentive to those considering judicial review 
defaultwhose
default cases h
defaultave no merit …”.  In this regard, we point to our consultation response at paragraphs 25-30 where we attempt to compare the progress and success of claims that are legally aided and those that are not.  As we stated there
default in summary
default (para 30), “
defaultthere is no
defaultthing to suggest legally aided judicial review claims are pursued in a reckless way that results in a relatively high number of “weak” cases. On the contrary, there is everything to suggest that legally aided cases appear to be handled far more cautiously 
defaultthan those which are unfunded, and lawyers in legally-aided applications are far more likely only to pursue cases with merit
default.” 
default13.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe welcome the more detailed data 
defaultand analysis 
defaultprovided in the Impact Assessment attached to the 
defaultJudicial Review: Further Propos
defaultals
default 
defaultpaper
default at paras 15-40
default.
default  Having said this, 
defaultwe note that there is substantial uncertainty about the impact and effects, including how claimants may choose to respond if legal aid is unavailable, and we note especially the issue of claimants possibly proce
defaulteding as litigants in person (para 38 of the Impact Assessment). We also
default remain concerned that the data is not presented in a way that offers some comparison of how legally aided claims proceed as against non-legally aided claims. Our tentative view is tha
defaultt, even with the further data provided, the 
defaultmethods used to achieve the projected 
defaultsavings are likely to have significant 
defaultdetrimental 
defaultimpacts on access to justice and, in the absence of comparative data, it is unclear that the prop
defaultosed changes are the best 
defaultand most appropriate pathway towards achieving the aim of acting as a disincentive to pursue unmeritorious cases.
default 
default  The numerous other concerns we have raised in our original response to the consultation also remain.
default   
default  
